title: For Sale:  MARLIN 1897  OCTAGONAL .22 TAKE DOWN LEVER ACTION 119 YEARS OLD
postcontent: 1st year production 24" octagonal barrel with optional BEECH COMBINATION FRONT SIGHT & Rocky Mountain rear,  full length magazine tube that feeds short, long, and long rifle ammo interchangably, American black walnut straight uncheckered stock. The finish is mostly smooth gray, the rifling in the bore is rough (not much Kleenbore ammo in the late 1800's), there is a 1/4" wide X 3/4" long chip off the toe of the stock, rest of wood is very good. title: For Sale:  1944 Springfield M1 Garand O-66 USMCCMP Service Grade
postcontent: It’s extremely rare that you know what service a Garand belonged to. This one is marked O-66 on the receiver which means it went through a USMC rebuild (Overhaul) in 1966 and then went into storage. They only marked the receivers for a few years. O-66 marked Garands are prized because they’re often in nearly unissued condition. According to Scott Duff they’re so well thought of it was common for The CMP to give them as one of the prizes for winning a CMP shooting competition. If you google “O-66 Marine Garand” you can find more information on O-66 Garands. With the low barrel wear it would be fine to take it to the range as much as you want. It’s a non-import CMP Service Grade 1944 Springfield Armory in Superior Condition with all USGI parts. The Springfield barrel has a like new muzzle reading of 1 and a throat reading of 3. Take a look at the pictures of the receiver, it’s gorgeous with a beautiful patina and modest wear. I’ve shot 3 clips and it functioned with no issues. It has an appropriate un-humped cylinder lock and SA Op-Rod, bolt, trigger housing, hammer and a walnut CMP stock.
